h3. Issue Summary:

The [UserPicker|https://developer.atlassian.com/platform/forge/ui-kit/components/user-picker/] component exhibits unexpected behaviour when used within a [popup|https://developer.atlassian.com/platform/forge/ui-kit/components/popup/], including issues with clearing selections and inadvertently closing the popup when a user is selected.

This issue is intermittent and primarily occurs after the second instance of opening and closing the popup.

Upon investigation, there is also known incompatibility with clearing the UserPicker’s defaultValues which requires clearing twice for changes to be reflected in the UI.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a Forge app in Confluence that uses the Popup and User Picker component. 
 # Try and use the following code for the frontend/index.jsx below::
 # 
{code:java}
import React, { useState } from 'react';
import ForgeReconciler, { Box, Button, Popup, Stack, UserPicker, xcss } from '@forge/react';const contentStyles = xcss({
  padding: 'space.200',
  display: 'flex',
  flexDirection: 'column',
  gap: 'space.100',
});const App = () => {
  const [isOpen, setIsOpen] = useState(false);  const defaultValues = [
    'xxxxx', // Default value for the first UserPicker, change to an atlassian id
    'xxxxx', // Default value for the second UserPicker, change to an atlassian id     'xxxxx', // Default value for the third UserPicker, change to an atlassian id   ];
  return (
    <Popup
      isOpen={isOpen}
      onClose={() => setIsOpen(false)}
      placement="bottom-start"
      content={() => (
        <Box xcss={contentStyles}>
          {[1, 2, 3].map((index) => (
            <UserPicker
              key={index}
              isMulti
              label={`Assignee ${index}`}
              placeholder="Select a user"
              name={`user-${index}`}
              description={`The selected user(s) will be assigned to this task ${index}`}
              onChange={(user) => console.log(`UserPicker ${index}:`, user)}
              defaultValue={defaultValues[index - 1]}
            />
          ))}
        </Box>
      )}
      trigger={() => (
        <Button
          appearance="primary"
          isSelected={isOpen}
          onClick={() => setIsOpen(!isOpen)}
        >
          {isOpen ? 'Close' : 'Open'} popup
        </Button>
      )}
    />
  );
};
ForgeReconciler.render(
  <React.StrictMode>
    <App />
  </React.StrictMode>
); {code}

h3. Expected Results
 * Users should be able to clear existing selections and add new ones without issues.

 * Selecting a user should not close the popup unless explicitly intended.

 * Clearing the UserPicker’s {{defaultValues}} should update the UI immediately without needing to clear twice.

h3. Actual Results
 * -Users are sometimes unable to clear selections or add new ones.- resolved

 * -Selecting a user may cause the popup to close unexpectedly.- resolved

 * Clearing the UserPicker’s {{defaultValues}} requires doing so twice for the UI to update.

h3. Workaround

Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. Issue Summary

Connect condition {{user_is_project_admin}} does not restrict users correctly
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a Connect app for Jira;
 # Add the following condition to a module: {{user_is_project_admin}}
 # Access the module with a project admin account and verify that the resource is accessible;

 # Log in with a user that is not an admin of the project and attempt to access the module;

h3. Expected Results

The user is not allowed because the condition checks whether the user is a project admin, which it is not.
h3. Actual Results

The module loads regardless of whether the user is an admin of the project or not
h3. Workaround

Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3.Steps to Reproduce
# Create a Delegated Directory in Crowd *pre-2.7* (e.g. Crowd 2.5.2). Make sure that the *Synchronise User Details* checkbox is checked, otherwise, the user rename feature will fail no matter what (not related to this bug)
# Login with a couple of users in the delegated directory (so that their accounts are created in the cwd_user table)
# Shutdown Crowd
# Upgrade to Crowd 2.7 (tested with the in-place database upgrade method)
# Run the following query in the Crowd Database:
{code}
SELECT * FROM cwd_user WHERE user_name = '<username>';
{code}
Replace <username> with the user that is affected. Notice that their *external_id* is NULL (which is why this bug occurs).
# Rename the user in the LDAP server itself 
# Login with the new username. If you check the cwd_user table now, you will notice that there are now 2 accounts created for the same user, 1 with the old username and 1 with the new username

h3.Workaround
After the Crowd upgrade to Crowd 2.7 , make sure all users login to their accounts *at least once*, before you proceed to rename any of their usernames in the LDAP server, to avoid breaking Crowd and other Crowd-connected applications. Always check the following to see if there are any users left, with a NULL external_id:
{code}
SELECT * FROM cwd_user WHERE external_id IS NULL;
{code}

h3.Suggestion
We need to have an upgrade task to force an external_id sync with the LDAP server during/immediately after the upgrade, for all users in the delegated directory

