item.description:
h3. Issue Summary
For projects, when using the API, or when viewing inspecting the object in the UI, the avatar resource link is returned in the following JSON object:
{code}
    },
    "html": {
      "href": "https://bitbucket.org/<workspaceID>/workspace/projects/<projectKey>/avatar"
    },
{code}

However, this is not the case with repositories' and workspaces' avatars. These resources are available in  the following format instead for repositories and workspaces:
{code}
    "avatar": {
      "href": "https://bytebucket.org/ravatar/%7B<UUID>%7D"
    },
{code}

The impact of this is that, for repositories and workspaces, the avatar image can be viewed publicly, without requiring users to be logged into Bitbucket. This is inconsistent with the behavior of projects, which require the user to be authenticated before redirecting to the appropriate resource in S3.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
There are two ways to reproduce this:
First option:
 # Navigate to any project in the UI;
 # Open the devtools console (F12) and click on the avatar for the project
 # You should see that the reference for the avatar resource is https://bitbucket.org/<workspaceID>/workspace/projects/<projectKey>

Second option:
 # Use the following Bitbucket API endpoint 
{code}
https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/workspaces/{workspace}/projects/{project_key}
{code}
 # Check the response. The project avatar object will look like this:
{code}
    },
    "html": {
      "href": "https://bitbucket.org/<workspaceID>/workspace/projects/<projectKey>/avatar"
    },
{code}

h3. Expected Results
The Avatar reference to the resource should reference the appropriate bytebucket link in the API and UI, like so:
{code}
https://bytebucket.org/ravatar/%7B<UUID>%7D
{code}

This will allow users to access the avatar resource without authentication, to be consistent with other endpoints such as repositories and workspaces.

h3. Actual Results
Bitbucket references the following link to redirect to the Avatar resource for projects, both on API and UI:
{code}
https://bitbucket.org/<workspaceID>/workspace/projects/<projectKey>/avatar
{code}

h3. Workaround
 Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. Issue Summary

Next link for Pagination in Bitbucket API uses workspace and repo slugs instead of IDs which breaks forge apps.

This affects many APIs including [List Commits|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/bitbucket/rest/api-group-commits/#api-repositories-workspace-repo-slug-commits-get] and [List pipeline variables|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/bitbucket/rest/api-group-pipelines/#api-repositories-workspace-repo-slug-pipelines-config-variables-get] etc will have a next page link like this.

For example, [List pipeline variables|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/bitbucket/rest/api-group-pipelines/#api-repositories-workspace-repo-slug-pipelines-config-variables-get] will have next link in the following format.

{code}
"next": "https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/${workspace_slug}/${repo_slug}/pipelines_config/variables?page=2&pagelen=10",
{code}

If we try to use this with [Forge routeFromAbsolute|https://developer.atlassian.com/platform/forge/apis-reference/fetch-api-product.requestbitbucket/#absolute-path-construction--routefromabsolute-] then we get a 400 - INVALID_TARGET_URL error.

{code}
const fetchVariables = async (workspaceId, repositoryId) => {
    const res = await api
        .asApp()
        .requestBitbucket(route`/2.0/repositories/${workspaceId}/${repositoryId}/pipelines_config/variables`);
   
    const data = await res.json();
    
    const res2 = await api
  .asApp()
  .requestBitbucket(routeFromAbsolute(`${data.next}`)); // calling the second page here.

  const data2 = await res2.json();

    return data2;
};
{code} 

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a Forge app for Bitbucket
 # Using *requestBitbucket* call the next page using the link received in the first response

h3. Expected Results
The next page can be retrieved using the next link

h3. Actual Results

we get a 400 - INVALID_TARGET_URL error. Because, *requestBitbucket* expects workspace and repo IDs in the link and not slugs.
!invalid_url.png|width=300!

h3. Workaround

We can increase the pagelen (i.e. ?pagelen=500) in the first call to retrieve all the responses in a single call to avoid pagination.

