This manifests itself in a complete inability for Bitbucket Pipelines to use AWS CDK's NodejsFunction.

It seems like this issue happens when some Linux tool like `tar`, `cp` changes OWNER of files. So, you need to find out that step in your docker image file. And change owner again in the same step (same context).

For example. Let's say following line was created file with a different owner 

 
{code:java}
RUN curl https://example.com/example.tar.gz | tar xvz 
{code}
Then you need to do turn back to your docker "owner" user, For example: when the owner is "root" should be like follows
{code:java}
RUN curl https://example.com/example.tar.gz | tar xvz && chown -R root:root ./
{code}
if introduces a conditional clause More (Definitions, Synonyms, Translation)

> Fixed the Bitbucket pipeline build problem, but also increases the size of our Docker image because Docker makes a copy of all of the files that are modified (contents or filesystem flags). We will look again at multi-stage builds to reduce the size of our docker images.
@Jason Harrison,
to keep the size of final Docker image small, do NOT override anything related to the prior stages in the final one. For example, the following will lead to the increased size: {code:java} FROM ... as stage_1 ...
FROM ... as stage_2 ...
FROM ... # final image
... COPY --from=stage_2 /opt/tomcat /opt/ RUN chown -R root:root /opt/tomcat ...{code}
a trick will be to copy properly and/or modify at an earlier stage: {code:java} FROM ... as stage_1 ...
FROM tomcat:9-jdk11-openjdk-slim as stage_2 ... # whatever is needed RUN chmod -R o-rwx "${CATALINA_HOME}" && \ chmod 750 "${CATALINA_HOME}/logs" "${CATALINA_HOME}/temp" && \ rm -rf "${JAVA_HOME}"/jmods \ "${JAVA_HOME}"/demo \ "${JAVA_HOME}"/man \ "${CATALINA_HOME}"/native-jni-lib \ "${CATALINA_HOME}"/webapps.dist \ "${CATALINA_HOME}"/webapps/*
FROM ... # final image ... COPY --chown=${my_user}:${my_group} --from=stage_2 /opt/tomcat /opt/ ... {code}

