h3. Workaround

manually splitting arguments in your scripts using the command {_}$serverArray = $serverlist.Split(','){_}, which you have already implemented.

h3. Issue Summary

When running a Cleanup Task as part of a Job, Bamboo will report a {{NoSuchFileException}} in case one of the to-be-deleted files or folders is not available during the task execution – E.g. it was deleted by an external process during the Task execution – even if the resulting build directory ends up cleaned up.

The issue also happens when a symlink on Windows is to be deleted, but Bamboo deletes its target location before the actual symlink. This is an expected behaviour on Windows and Bamboo should be able to gracefully accept the error.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a Plan with a Job containing:
 ** Cleanup Task
 ** The following PowerShell Script
{code:visualbasic}
# Define relative paths for the target directory and the link location
$relativeTargetPath = "custom\sxa\celt"
$relativeLinkBasePath = "node_modules\@sxa"

# Ensure the target directory exists
if (-Not (Test-Path -Path $relativeTargetPath)) {
    Write-Host "The target path ($relativeTargetPath) does not exist. Creating it..."
    New-Item -Path $relativeTargetPath -ItemType Directory -Force
}

# Resolve the target path to an absolute path
$targetPath = Resolve-Path -Path $relativeTargetPath

# Create a sample file in the target directory
$sampleFilePath = Join-Path -Path $targetPath -ChildPath "sample.txt"
if (-Not (Test-Path -Path $sampleFilePath)) {
    Write-Host "Creating a sample file at $sampleFilePath"
    Set-Content -Path $sampleFilePath -Value "This is a sample file for testing."
}

# Ensure the base directory for the link exists
if (-Not (Test-Path -Path $relativeLinkBasePath)) {
    Write-Host "Creating directories for the junction path..."
    New-Item -Path $relativeLinkBasePath -ItemType Directory -Force
}

# Define the full path for the link
$relativeLinkPath = Join-Path -Path $relativeLinkBasePath -ChildPath "celt"

# Check if the link already exists and remove it if necessary
if (Test-Path -Path $relativeLinkPath) {
    Write-Host "The junction already exists. Removing the existing junction..."
    Remove-Item -Path $relativeLinkPath -Force
}

# Create the junction
try {
    Write-Host "Creating junction..."
    New-Item -Path $relativeLinkPath -ItemType Junction -Target $targetPath
    Write-Host "Junction created successfully from $relativeLinkPath to $targetPath"
} catch {
    Write-Host "Failed to create junction: $_"
    exit 1
}

# Verify if the sample file is accessible through the junction
$linkedFilePath = Join-Path -Path $relativeLinkPath -ChildPath "sample.txt"
if (Test-Path -Path $linkedFilePath) {
    Write-Host "The sample file is available through the junction at $linkedFilePath"
} else {
    Write-Host "The sample file is NOT available through the junction."
}

# Remove the entire 'celt' source folder
Write-Host "Removing the entire 'celt' source folder..."
Remove-Item -Path $targetPath -Recurse -Force

# Final verification to ensure the junction still works
if (Test-Path -Path $linkedFilePath) {
    Write-Host "The junction is still valid, and the 'celt' folder has been removed from the source."
} else {
    Write-Host "The junction is not functioning as expected after removing the source folder."
}
{code}
 # Associate the Job with a Bamboo Agent running on Windows
 # Run the Plan twice

h3. Expected Results
 * The Plan should succeed on both runs

h3. Actual Results
 * The Plan succeeds on the first run but fails on the second time reporting a:
{noformat}
Error occurred while running Task '(1)' of type com.atlassian.bamboo.plugins.bamboo-artifact-downloader-plugin:cleanWorkingDirectoryTask.
com.atlassian.bamboo.task.TaskException: Unable to clean working directory
{noformat}

h3. Workaround
 * Replace the Cleanup Task with a Script Task and remove the contents of the folder

